{{Use Australian English|date=March 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}} The '''Australian Labor Party split of 1916''' occurred following severe disagreement within the [[Australian Labor Party]] over the issue of proposed [[World War I conscription in Australia]]. Labor [[Prime Minister of Australia]] [[Billy Hughes]] had, by 1916, become an enthusiastic supporter of conscription as a means to boost Australia's contribution to the war effort. On 30 August 1916, he announced plans for a referendum on the issue (the [[Australian plebiscite, 1916]]), and introduced enabling legislation into parliament on 14 September, which passed only with the support of the opposition. Six of Hughes' ministers resigned in protest at the move, and the New South Wales state branch of the Labor Party expelled Hughes. The referendum saw an intense campaign in which Labor figures vehemently advocated on each side of the argument, although the "no" campaign narrowly won on 14 November. In the wake of the referendum defeat, the caucus moved to expel Hughes on 14 November; instead, he and 23 supporters resigned and formed the [[National Labor Party]]. [[Frank Tudor]] was elected leader of the [[rump party]]. Hughes was recommissioned as Prime Minister, heading a minority government supported by the opposition [[Commonwealth Liberal Party]]; the two parties then merged as the [[Nationalist Party of Australia]] and won the [[Australian federal election, 1917|1917 federal election]]. The Nationalist Party served as the main conservative party of Australia until 1931, and the split resulted in many early Labor figures ending their careers on the political right.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nma.gov.au/primeministers/william_hughes | title=William Hughes | publisher=National Museum of Australia | work=Prime Ministers of Australia | accessdate=31 August 2015}}</ref>
The split had different impacts in different states. In [[Queensland]] there was no significant split at all, with the [[Australian Labor Party (Queensland Branch)|state Labor Party]] having experienced the loss of many early members a decade earlier when [[William Kidston]] led [[Kidstonites|a breakaway group]] out in 1907.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |last=Wanka |first=K.J. |editor1-last=Murphy |editor1-first=Denis Joseph |editor2-last=Joyce |editor2-first=Roger Bilbrough |editor3-last=Hughes |editor3-first=Colin A. |encyclopedia=Prelude to Power: The Rise of the Labour Party in Queensland 1885-1915 |title=William Kidston - The Dilemma of the Powerful Leader |date=1970 |publisher=Jacaranda Press |isbn=9780701603120 |page=205}}</ref> During the war [[Premier of Queensland|Premier]] [[T. J. Ryan]] made strong efforts to minimise losses.<ref>{{cite book |last=Murphy |first=D.J. |author-link1=Denis Murphy (Australian politician) |date=1975 |title=T J Ryan: A Political Biography |publisher=University of Queensland Press |pages=186-208 |isbn=9780702222894 }}</ref> Only one member of the state parliament, [[John Adamson (Queensland politician)|John Adamson]], left the party and initially there was no attempt to create an alternate vehicle at the state level. However in October 1919 Adamson was part of the formation of a [[National Labor Party (Queensland)|National Labor Party]] for ex-Labor supporters that used the name.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/179391506 |title=20 Oct 1919 - THE DAILY MIRROR |publisher=Trove |date=1919-10-20 |accessdate=2018-06-26}}</ref> It had no electoral success and soon disappeared.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Irving |first1=Baiba |last2=Schedvin |first2=Bernie |date=May 1973 |title=A Confidential Report on Nationalist Organisation in Queensland, 1920 |journal=Queensland Heritage |volume=2 |issue=8 |page=15n }}</ref>
==See also== *[[History of the Australian Labor Party#World War I conscription and the split of 1916]] *[[Australian Labor Party split of 1931]] *[[Australian Labor Party split of 1955]]
