{{Party politics}}
'''Far-left politics''' are political views located further on the left of the [[Left–right political spectrum|left-right spectrum]] than the standard [[Left-wing politics|political left]].  

The term has been used to describe ideologies such as: [[communism]], [[anarcho-communism]], [[left-communism]], [[anarcho-syndicalism]], [[Marxism–Leninism]], [[Trotskyism]], and [[Maoism]].<ref name="dawson">Left Communism in Australia, by J.A. Dawson ''Thesis 11'']</ref><ref>Left Communism and Trotskyism, by Loren Goldner et al.</ref>

== Europe ==
{{see also|List of left and far-left parties in Europe}}
[[File:NPA Révolution tunisienne Planoise.jpg|thumb|French posters of support to the [[Tunisian Revolution]] (and [[feminism]] below)]]
Luke March of the School of Social and Political Science at the [[University of Edinburgh]] defines the far-left in Europe as those who position themselves to the left of [[social democracy]], which they see as insufficiently left-wing. The two main sub-types are called the radical left, who desire fundamental changes to the [[Capitalism|capitalist]] system yet remain accepting of liberal democracy, and the extreme left, who are more hostile to [[liberal democracy]] and denounce any compromise with capitalism. March specifies four major subgroups within contemporary European far-left politics: [[Communism|communists]], [[Democratic socialism|democratic socialists]], [[Left-wing populism|populist socialists]] and [[Populism#Populist socialism|social populists]].<ref name="March">{{cite book|last1=March|first1=Luke|title=Contemporary Far Left Parties in Europe: From Marxism to the Mainstream?|date=2008|publisher=Friedrich-Ebert-Stiftung|location=Berlin|isbn=9783868720006|page=3|url=http://library.fes.de/pdf-files/id/ipa/05818.pdf|accessdate=3 June 2017}}</ref>

Vít Hloušek and Lubomír Kopeček add secondary characteristics to those identified by March and Mudde, such as [[anti-Americanism]], [[anti-globalization movement|anti-globalization]], opposition to [[NATO]] and rejection of [[European integration]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hloušek|first1=Vít|last2=Kopeček|first2=Lubomír|title=Origin, Ideology and Transformation of Political Parties: East-Central and Western Europe Compared|date=2010|publisher=Ashgate|location=Farnham|isbn=9780754678403|page=46}}</ref>

In [[France]], the term ''extrême-gauche'' ("far-left") is a generally accepted term for political groups that position themselves to the left of the [[Socialist Party (France)|Socialist Party]], such as [[Trotskyism|Trotskyists]], [[Marxism-Leninism-Maoism|Maoists]], [[anarchist communism|anarcho-communists]] and [[New Left]]ists. Some, such as political scientist Serge Cosseron, limit the scope to the left of the [[French Communist Party]],<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cosseron|first1=Serge|title=Dictionnaire de l'extrême gauche|date=2007|publisher=Larousse|location=Paris|isbn=2035826209|page=20}}</ref> but there is no real consensus.

== Far-left terrorism ==
{{main|Left-wing terrorism}}
{{see also|Operation Gladio}}
[[File:RAF-Bombenanschlag in Ramstein, 1981.jpg|thumb|Aftermath of the bombing on American [[Ramstein Air Base]] in 1981 by [[Left-wing terrorism|left-wing terrorist]] group [[Rote Armee Fraktion|RAF]]]]
There were many far-left [[militant]] organizations formed from existing political parties in the 1960s and 1970s,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Weinberg|first1=Leonard|last2=Pedahzur|first2=Ami|last3=Perliger|first3=Arie|title=Political Parties and Terrorist Groups|date=2009|publisher=Routledge|location=London|isbn=9781135973377|page=53|edition=2nd}}</ref> such as the [[Red Brigades]] and the [[Red Army Faction]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Chaliand|first1=Gérard|title=The History of Terrorism: From Antiquity to Al Qaeda|date=2010|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley, California|isbn=9780520247093}}</ref> These groups generally aimed to overthrow capitalism and the wealthy ruling classes.

