The Liberal Party's '''Senior Whip''' was a political post with the task of administering the "[[Whip (politics)|whipping in]]" system attempting to ensure that party MPs attend and vote according to the party leadership's wishes.{{sfn|Wilson|1985|p=278}} All Liberal whips were members of the House of Representatives with none coming from the [[New Zealand Legislative Council|Legislative Council]]. The position held high esteem in the Liberal caucus and it was not uncommon for whips to move in to higher positions later on. Two ([[William MacDonald (New Zealand politician)|William MacDonald]] and [[George Forbes (New Zealand politician)|George Forbes]]) would later serve as party leader. Forbes also served as Prime Minister from 1930 to 1935.<ref name="DNZB Forbes">{{DNZB|Gardner|W. J.|3f9|Forbes, George William|11 December 2011}}</ref>
